erable than it should have been. Not Working is about how people want full-time work at a decent wage and how the plight of the underemployed contributes to widespread despair, a worsening drug epidemic, and the unchecked rise of right-wing populism. David Blanchflower explains why the economy since the Great Recession is vastly different from what came before, and calls out our leaders for their continued failure to address one of the most unacknowledged social catastrophes of our time. This revelatory and outspoken book is his candid report on how the young and the less skilled are among the worst casualties of underemployment, how immigrants are taking the blame, and how the epidemic of unhappiness and self-destruction will continue to spread unless we deal with it. Especially urgent now, Not Working is an essential guide to strengthening the labor market for all when we need it most.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDisguised unemployment-Great Britain. 0aDisguised unemployment. 0aGreat Britain-Economic conditions-21st century. 0aLabor demand. 0aLabor market. 0aLabor supply. 0aUnderemployment-Great Britain. 0aUnderemployment. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh  aAmericans.  aAndy Haldane.  aAusterity.  aBank of England.  aBank rate.  aBusiness cycle.  aCapitalism.  aCentral bank.  aChief economist.  aCompetition.  aCouncil of Economic Advisers.  aCulture war.  aCurrent population survey (US).  aDavid Blanchflower.  aDebt.  aDeveloped country.  aDonald Trump.  aDownside risk.  aEconomic growth.  aEconomic inequality.  aEconomics.  aEconomist.  aEconomy of the United States.  aEconomy.  aEmployment.  aEurobarometer.  aEurostat.  aExternal examiner.  aFederal Open Market Committee.  aFinancial crisis of 2007–08.  aFinancial crisis.  aF